    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-01-03T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-01-03T00:00:00-05:00" n="1473"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1473">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 312.41/70.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        Vice Consul <persName type="to">Simpich</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-01-03">
                            <hi rend="italic">January 3, 1914</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Department’s December 6. Department now informed Villa has seized about eight
                    hundred head of cattle from Keays, British subject, at Palomas, Chihuahua, on
                    which he paid to Constitutionalist Government one thousand dollars gold export
                    duty. Villa refuses to permit Keays to cross the cattle to United States. You
                    will ask that cattle be returned to Keays and that he be permitted to pass them
                    out of Mexico.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">J. B. Moore</hi>
                    </signed>.</closer>
            </div>
        </body>
